              margin-top: 2px !important;">What are duration and convexity?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-9-3.jpg" alt="What are duration and convexity?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><strong>Duration</strong> and convexity are critical concepts in fixed-income investing. These help investors understand the sensitivity of bond prices to interest rate changes. Duration measures the average time to receive all cash flows (coupon payments and principal) from a bond. It indicates a bond‚Äôs price sensitivity to changes in interest rates. Higher-duration bonds are more sensitive to rate changes.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><strong>Convexity</strong> complements duration by measuring how the duration of a bond changes as interest rates shift. The difference is that it considers the fact that the relationship between bond prices and interest rates is not linear. Bonds with higher convexity are less affected by large rate changes and offer more price stability. Together, duration and convexity provide a clearer picture of interest rate risk.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
